      <hedline>
        <hl1>Thank You, Mr. Vonnegut</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rachel Betesh letter praises Kurt Vonnegut (April 12 obituary)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Kurt Vonnegut Is Dead at 84; Caught Imagination of His Age'' (front page, April 12):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Kurt Vonnegut Is Dead at 84; Caught Imagination of His Age'' (front page, April 12):</p>
        <p>Kurt Vonnegut's novels sit dog-eared and underlined on my bookshelf, as they do on bookshelves in libraries and dormitories everywhere.</p>
        <p>Six years ago, after the deaths of my grandfather and my dog, I wrote Mr. Vonnegut a letter. It was to be an appreciation for ''Bluebeard,'' which I had finished that morning. It became an 18-year-old's earnest attempt to thank someone she loved, ''before it was too late.''</p>
        <p>It must have been just awkward enough to be endearing. Almost a year later, I received a handwritten, illustrated card from New York.</p>
        <p>''Dearest Rachel,'' it began, ''I did indeed receive your letter. I liked both you and it a whole lot.''</p>
        <p>Like avid readers and awkward teenagers across the country -- and back through the decades -- I'll miss Mr. Vonnegut for his candor, humor and relevance.</p>
        <p>Rachel Betesh  Oakland, Calif., April 12, 2007</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
